<p>While completing her master&#8217;s in the US, she worked as a Technical Programme Manager at the network, building systems that connected the tech teams to finance, HR, legal, and editorial. Where other people saw “operations,” she saw a backstage wiring that made a global newsroom run.</p>



<p>When she graduated in 2018, Al Jazeera went a step further. The company filed a freelance contractor visa so she could relocate to Qatar. When she landed in Doha, the country&#8217;s capital city, she converted it into a full-time residency permit.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The <a href="https://www.mol.gov.qa/En/Services/Pages/ServiceDetails.aspx?itemid=75" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">freelance visa</a>, which often requires sponsorship from a local entity, allowed Uyanna to legally live and work in the country for two years, opening a new chapter in her life in the Middle East.</p>



